{"source_key":"sha256-5554f84e350d12a12ce22886a954582c","record_index":1228,"record_hash":"sha256:227111d08a1d647046e61ee2d9fdc53f30111e0cd2f4b2244d5a08272df01401","timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:29.251Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1408](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1408) `get_session_timeline_hydrates_records_in_turn_order` doesn’t actually prove order: it has one turn and one record. Worth changing to either two records in one capture, asserting hydrated record texts in detail order, or two captures with `None`, asserting turns come back old-to-new. Right now a bad unordered implementation could still pass.\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1420](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1420) The `capture_kind` and `record_count` asserts feel like duplication from the capture/storage tests. For this test’s intent, I’d trim them and keep `session_key`, turn count, record count/shape only as needed to safely index, and the hydrated `kind/text`.\\n\\n- [crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1428](/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/gitmeta.rs:1428) The window test is good and small. It protects the important behavior: `Some(1)` returns the latest turn and hydrates that turn’s records. I wouldn’t add cases for `Some(0)` or oversized windows unless the API contract explicitly cares; those are implementation-edgey and not worth the test weight.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T15:41:29.251Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}